files.\\n\\nLooking at the current implementation though, post-apply gets skipped when `--root` is set because `GitTools.FindRepoRoot()` would locate the actual repository rather than the copy. But for testing on a copy, we actually need post-apply to verify the transition works correctly. The internal checker can work on the copy since it takes the workstate and log paths as parameters, but projection relies on finding the real repo root internally, which creates a problem for copy-based testing. For the rollback test, the seam fires right after the atomic write succeeds, so we never reach projection—we go straight into the rollback handler with the preimage already saved.\\n\\nIn --root mode, we skip projection during rollback and consider it successful if the hash matches. But this creates a gap in the FATAL taxonomy: if projection fails during rollback in non-root mode, we end up in STATE_RESTORED_PROJECTION_NOT_VERIFIED, which is different from the post-apply failure case.\\n\\nFor the test in copy mode, I should use `HandoffIntegrityChecker.Run()` with explicit paths as the post-apply check. If that fails and we successfully rollback with a matching hash, we exit 1 with ROLLED_BACK status. The \\\"projection 성공\\\" part of ROLLED_BACK means re-projecting after rollback to ensure the projection files stay in sync with the restored state.\\n\\nThe cleanest approach is to branch on whether `--root` is set: in canonical mode, run the full projection plus internal checker after applying changes; in copy mode, skip projection entirely and only run the internal checker. Similarly, after rollback, attempt projection in canonical mode but skip it in copy mode. This way, ROLLED_BACK in copy mode simply means the hash was restored and the internal checker passed.\\n\\nBut there's a complication—`ProjectionCli.Run()` uses `GitTools.FindRepoRoot()` to traverse upward looking for `.git`, which may not exist in a temporary copy directory.\\n\\nActually, looking at the directive more carefully, it says to copy the repo and replace specific files with known-good versions, which means the temp copy does include `.git`. So when `ProjectionCli.Run()` calls `GitTools.FindRepoRoot()` from within that temp copy, it should find the temp copy's root, not the original repo.\\n\\nBut wait—we're running `dotnet run --project server ...` from the real repo's directory, so `GitTools.FindRepoRoot()` would actually find the real repo instead. That means using `--root <temp_copy_path>` would still write projection files to the real repo, which is why the current code skips post-apply in `--root` mode.\\n\\nFor the test cases using temp copies, we're really testing the state machine logic—reconciliation, hash checks, idempotency—not the projection behavior itself. The \\\"projection 성공\\\" part of the ROLLED_BACK FATAL taxonomy is meant for production scenarios.\\n\\nSo my approach is: in canonical mode run the full post-apply with projection and internal checker, but in copy mode with `--root` set, only run the internal checker and skip projection. For ROLLED_BACK recovery, canonical mode restores the preimage and re-runs projection with hash verification, while copy mode just restores and verifies the hash.\\n\\nNow I need to figure out which tests should use temp copies versus canonical mode—Test 2 and 3 need temp copies since they're based on fixture-c with valid canonical IDs, but Test 4 with the hand-forged scenario should run on canonical.\\n\\nTest 4 runs apply on the canonical WORKSTATE where it has the corrupted DI0004-BLOCKED-CODEX entry and expects a state-corrupted-preapply exit. Tests 5 through 9 all use temp copies for their specific scenarios—collision detection, v1 log entries, byte tampering, rollback with test seams, and various fatal injection points. Test 10 could go either way but Test 11 needs canonical mode to check for legacy callers.\\n\\nFor the canonical tests, I need to prepare an envelope on canonical first, then apply it—th