ding precondition checks... Writing build check logic... I need to update the test cases to verify the new flags are properly set. I'm adding checks for `phaseChangeReady` and `replayReady` in the declare-ok test, plus creating separate test cases for extra known subjects exception, production precondition not being default true, and build verdict not being forged. Looking at the directive more carefully, the record-ready-flags-complete check should be integrated into the existing declare-ok test since the record is already created there. I need to trace through the fixture state after each test case to understand what record exists at each step. After case 1 creates the record, case 2 just reads it, but case 3 deletes it via ResetFixture and then runs a failing declare. Case 5 creates a new record, so by the time I reach case 6, I'm working with that newer record—but case 6 will also delete it through ResetFixture. I should reorder the test cases so that case 8 (checking the ready flags) runs right after case 5 when a valid record exists, rather than as a separate case. Then cases 6, 7, and 9 can follow. I'm also considering whether to fold the ready flags check directly into the declare success case instead of making it standalone. So with the new code, when `precon.BuildVerified=false`, the `buildOk` flag gets set to false, which triggers an exit with the precondition error message and prevents any record from being created—exactly what we need. The old code had a similar check but I'm comparing how the logic flows differently now.\\n\\nThe key insight is that the old self-test couldn't properly test the production path where `precon=null` because it only tested the explicit failure case. The new approach lets me test the production scenario by using `precon=null` with a failing build in the temp directory, which is more realistic. I should keep the two test cases separate: one for verifying that production mode refuses to proceed without explicit flags, and another for catching forged build verdicts. I need to verify whether `RunSelfTestInDir` passes those new parameters to `RunDeclareCore`, and since it doesn't yet, the test cases will use the defaults (both false). For existing tests like `RunCaseDeclareOk` that need to succeed, the precon values take precedence over CLI flags anyway, so when `precon.AutoLauncherOff=true` and `precon.HighRiskClosed=true`, those will be used regardless. For the production preconditions test case, I'm setting up a scenario where those flags aren't provided.\\n\\nI'm also tracing through the logic for `RunCaseBuildVerdictNotForged` where the precon has `BuildVerified=false`, which should cause an exit with no record. Now I need to update all the callers of `CheckAllPreconditions` since its signature is changing—currently it's only called from `RunDeclareCore`, so that's the main place to update.\\n\\n`RunDeclareCore` receives `autoLauncherVerified` and `highRiskVerified` from `RunDeclare`, which parses the CLI flags. The self-test cases call `RunDeclareCore` directly, and since the existing ones use a precon object (which overrides the flags), they'll work fine. The new production test cases will pass `TestPrecon=null` with `autoLauncherVerified=false`, which is the default anyway, so those should work too.\\n\\nNow I'm ready to write the actual code changes. Writing the modified file... I could handle this a few different ways—either require a value like `--auto-launcher-verified true`, modify ParseFlagMap to support standalone flags, or just check the args array directly. The cleanest approach is to use `Any()` to search for the flag's presence in the arguments, which avoids changing the existing parsing logic. Now I need to write out the complete updated file with minimal changes.\\n\\nLooking at the allowlist, I can modify TrustOriginCli.cs and CliRouter.cs if needed, but since the flag parsing happens inside the Run method, I probably don't need to touch the router. Let me focus on jus